'''''Dawn at Midnight''''' is a 2014 feature-length [[documentary film]] directed by [[Cetywa Powell]].

==Plot==
In 2013, [[Hezbollah]] entered Syria's war to defend President Bashar Al-Assad. ''Dawn at Midnight'' recounts Hezbollah's beginnings from a murky fringe group to the most powerful militia in their country and revisits the Lebanese hostage crisis, a period which saw 96 [[Lebanon hostage crisis|Westerners kidnapped]] and 9 killed during Lebanon's Civil War. The film was inspired by Robert Fisk's book ''Pity The Nation'', ''Hostage'' by Con Coughlin, and ''Man without a gun'' by Giandomenico Picco.

==Contributors==
* [[Terry A. Anderson]] - War journalist, kidnapped by Hezbollah and held hostage for six years and nine months.
* [[Giandomenico Picco]] - United Nations hostage negotiator: helped negotiate the release of the last 11 western hostages in Lebanon.
* [[Timur Goksel]] - United Nations spokesman

